27 Existing law sets forth certain fees applicable to certified court reporters and court
28 reporting firms. (NRS 656.220) Section 11.7 of this bill removes the amounts for such
29 fees and instead requires the Board to prescribe by regulation initial reasonable fees for
30 certified court reporters and court reporting firms. Section 11.7 requires those fees to be
31 equal to the fees set forth in existing law as of December 31, 2025. Section 11.7
32 authorizes the Board, after prescribing such initial fees, to increase or decrease a fee by
33 regulation to an amount that is not less than 90 percent and not more than 125 percent
34 of the current fee. Section 17.5 of this bill provides that the existing fees remain in effect
35 until the Board has established such fees by regulation. Sections 7 and 9 of this bill make
36 conforming changes to reflect the requirement imposed in section 11.7 that the Board
37 prescribe fees for certified court reporters by regulation.
38 Existing law authorizes certain courts and magistrates to designate a person who is not
39 required to be a certified court reporter to operate sound recording equipment to record
40 certain proceedings. (NRS 3.380, 4.400, 171.198) Section 16.3 of this bill similarly authorizes
41 a municipal court to make such a designation. [Section 2 of this bill exempts a person so
42 designated from the provisions of the Nevada Court Reporting and Legal Recording Law.
43 Section 5.3 of this bill replaces one member of the Board who is a certified court reporter
44 with a member who is a certified legal recorder, who is required to have been actively
45 engaged as a certified legal recorder for at least 5 years. Section 16.7 of this bill sets forth
46 certain exceptions to those requirements for such a member who is appointed before January
47 1, 2031. Section 13 authorizes a person who holds a certificate of registration as a legal video
48 recorder to use the title of “certified legal recorder” and the abbreviation “C.L.R.” and
49 prohibits any other person from using that title or abbreviation in connection with his or her
50 profession or business.
51 Section 4 of this bill authorizes a person who is not a party to certain civil proceedings to
52 request a copy of a transcript or legal record media of the proceeding from a court reporter,
53 legal recorder, court reporting firm or legal recording firm with possession of the transcript or
54 legal record media. Upon receipt of such a request, section 4 requires the court reporter, legal
55 recorder or firm to notify the parties to the proceeding or their attorneys of: (1) the request;
56 and (2) the name of the third-party requester. If the request is for a transcript or legal record
57 media of the testimony of an expert witness, unless a court order prohibits provision of the
58 transcript or record, section 4 requires the court reporter, legal recorder or firm to provide the
59 transcript or legal record media to the third-party requester not later than 60 days after
60 providing notice of the request and upon receipt of a reasonable fee prescribed by the court
61 reporter, legal recorder or firm. If the request is for a transcript or legal record media of the
62 proceeding other than the testimony of an expert witness, section 4 authorizes any party to the
63 proceeding to object to the provision of the transcript or video record media by providing
64 written notice to the court reporter, legal recorder or firm, the parties to the proceeding or their
65 attorneys and the third-party requester. If a party so objects, section 4 prohibits the court
66 reporter, legal recorder or firm from providing the requested transcript or legal record media
67 unless: (1) a court order authorizes provision of the transcript or legal record media; and (2)
68 the third-party requester pays a reasonable fee prescribed by the court reporter, legal recorder
69 or firm.

